{"id":"1303.3324","submitter":"Kwan-Woo Lee","authors":"Myung-Chul Jung, Chang-Jong Kang, B. I. Min, and K.-W. Lee","title":"Electronic Structures and Phonon Spectra in Boronitride Superconductors\n  LaMBN (M= Ni, Pt)","comments":"8 pages","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. B 87, 144509 (2013)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.87.144509","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.supr-con","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We have investigated electronic structures and phonon spectra of newly\ndiscovered isostructural superconductors LaNiBN (T_c = 4.1 K) and LaPtBN (T_c =\n6.7 K). We have found that their electronic structures are substantially\nthree-dimensional, leading to metallicity both in NiB (PtB) and the intervening\nLaN layers. Our ab initio phonon calculations show that almost all phonon modes\ncontribute to the electron-phonon coupling (EPC) mechanism, reflecting that\nboth layers are involved in the superconductivity. For LaNiBN, we obtain an EPC\nstrength of \\lambda = 0.52 and a logarithmically averaged characteristic phonon\nfrequency of \\omega_{log} = 376 K, leading to T_c = 3.9 K. Compared with the Ni\nB_{1g} mode in LaNiBN, the Pt B_{1g} mode in LaPtBN is reduced by ~70%, leading\nto a slightly enhanced \\lambda = 0.56 and an ~20 % reduced \\omega_{log}. The\nestimated T_c is 5.4 K for LaPtBN, in good agreement with the experiment. We do\nnot find any indication of magnetic instability for either LaNiBN or LaPtBN,\nwhich implies that both systems are EPC mediated superconductors. Further, we\nhave found an interesting trend of monotonic increase of T_c with respect to\nthe boron height in the NiB (PtB) layer of both borocarbide and boronitride\nsuperconductors, which suggests a possible way to enhance T_c in these systems.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 14 Mar 2013 01:09:16 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 15 Apr 2013 00:55:04 GMT"}],"update_date":"2013-04-19"}
